2.body: To get started with Liquip, you first need to understand some crucial parts of the plugin. In this chapter, we will discuss: Building and Installing the plugin Understanding the config format
2.title: Getting Started

3.body: To install the plugin you currently need to build it by yourself. In the following guide you will be taught to do so step by step.
3.title: Installation

4.body: To build the plugin you need the following: Java 17 or higher Git
4.title: Prerequisites

5.body: To install Java you can go to Adoptium . They provide prebuilt Java-binaries and even installers for Java.
5.title: Installing Java

6.body: To install Git you can go to https://git-scm.com/downloads and install git from there.
6.title: Installing Git

7.body: To set up the project you first need to clone the repository. To do so create a directory somewhere and open your terminal there and run the following command: git clone https://github.com/liquip/liquip-plugin.git . This will clone the repository into the current directory. Note that the directory must be empty to do so.
7.title: Setup

8.body: To now build the plugin you run the following command in the directory you cloned to: For Linux / macOS: ./gradlew build For Windows: .\gradlew.bat build If you have the gradle-cli installed you may also run the following: gradle build This should start gradle and build the plugin. The plugin is seperated into three submodules, being 'core', 'example-plugin' and 'gui'. The core-module is the Liquip-plugin. The example-plugin contains some experimental features. The gui-module contains the code for the inventory-guis. All three modules will be built but you most likely are just interested in the core-module. The output can be found in the core/build/libs directory. You want to take the jar-file without any '-dev' or '-all' in it and put it inside your plugins-directory.
8.title: Building

9.body: Many plugins use the YAML configuration-language . We instead use a different config-format. We think it is less error-prone as it does not rely on indentation. It is called HOCON and we recommend the .conf file-extension. You can read more about it here , but we will also explain the basics in this short guide.

9.title: The Config Format
